40|$|We {{study how}} {{changes in the}} {{barriers}} ex-felons face to restore their <b>voting</b> <b>rights</b> affect their political participation in Iowa. Prior to Executive Order 42, ex-felons were required to submit applications to request the restoration of their <b>voting</b> <b>rights.</b> We build an original dataset of who applied to have their <b>voting</b> <b>rights</b> restored and which of these applications were granted. These data reveal {{that only a small}} percentage of exfelons submitted applications. While most applications were granted, those submitted by individuals convicted of violent crimes, particularly sex crimes, were substantially more likely to be denied. The signing of Executive Order 42 in 2005 and Executive Order 70 in 2011 generates variation in whether ex-felons must submit applications to restore their <b>voting</b> <b>rights.</b> Our results show that eliminating applications increases ex-felon political participation, especially when ex-felons are notified that their <b>voting</b> <b>rights</b> are automatically restored...|$|R
