50|$|In some cases, the United States {{being one}} such case, some {{subnational}} entities have granted <b>voting</b> <b>rights</b> to non-citizens. Conceptions of subnational citizenship have been reasons to grant this right to those normally excluded from it. Other countries have granted <b>voting</b> <b>rights</b> to non-citizens who hold citizenship {{of a country}} which is a fellow member of a supranational organization (e.g. members of the European Union). In a few cases, countries grant <b>voting</b> <b>rights</b> to citizens and non-citizens alike.|$|R
